excerpt: Huge, interactive kids' museum including a planetarium, carousel, science labs & library.
detail_description: The Children's Museum of Indianapolis stands as a beacon of creativity and learning, proudly holding the title of the largest children's museum in the world. excerpt: Park home to a zoo, amphitheater & myriad cultural venues, plus a riverside trail & canal walk.

address: 801 W Washington St, Indianapolis, IN 46204, USA

With over 74,000 square feet of space including an outdoor amphitheater, it offers something for everyone from colorful fine art that appeals to young children to fascinating stories that history buffs will revel in.

The zoo offers interactive experiences including live feedings and trainer shows that appeal to all ages.

address: 1200 W Washington St, Indianapolis, IN 46222, USA

excerpt: Museum with a broad array of exhibits, ranging from fossils to pop culture, plus an IMAX theater.

Additionally, history enthusiasts will appreciate the opportunity to delve into Indiana's rich heritage, including connections to U.S.

address: 650 W Washington St, Indianapolis, IN 46204, USA

excerpt: Huge park with marina & beach, hiking & biking trails, wildlife-discovery centers, zip lines & more.

Visitors can also enjoy the brand new beer garden at the Garden Terrace.

Sports enthusiasts can also partake in year-round tours of nearby Lucas Oil Stadium.

address: 4790 W 16th St, Indianapolis, IN 46222, USA

excerpt: Guided tours & artifacts recount 19th-century medical history inside an 1890s pathology facility.

Visitors can also explore the Medical Plant Garden featuring over 120 medicinal plants from around the world.

address: 3270 Kirkbride Way, Indianapolis, IN 46222, USA

excerpt: Set within the famed racetrack, this museum showcases classic race cars & motorsports memorabilia.

The museum boasts an impressive collection of classic race cars, motorcycles, engines, and memorabilia dating back to the late 1800s. Visitors can immerse themselves in the rich history of racing in Indianapolis and explore winning cars from the renowned Indy 500.
name: Indianapolis Motor Speedway Museum
address: 4750 W 16th St, Indianapolis, IN 46222, USA

excerpt: Limestone monument with several sculptures & an observation level in square with many events.

address: Indianapolis, IN 46204, USA

address: 820 E 67th St, Indianapolis, IN 46220, USA

Visitors can explore various exhibits and artifacts that tell the story of the ship and its crew.

address: 55 E Michigan St, Indianapolis, IN 46204, USA

excerpt: Destination exploring the history of percussion, with exhibits, archive & drums to play.

The center showcases a diverse range of artifacts from different cultures, allowing guests to explore the cultural and historical significance of percussion in shaping music.

excerpt: Paved promenade hugging a canal popular for strolls, jogging & cycling, plus benches & coffee spots.

Along the way, visitors can admire colorful murals, charming bridges, and vibrant urban landscapes. The walk also features waterside eateries with inviting terraces that offer stunning views of the downtown skyline.

address: Indianapolis, IN, USA

The canal provides stunning views of the city skyline and is an ideal spot for a leisurely stroll, especially during sunset. Visitors can also explore the diverse shops and restaurants along the canal. Originally built for industrial purposes in the 19th century, the canal has been transformed into a recreational area with paddleboats and kayaks available for rent.

address: Indianapolis, IN 46204, USA

excerpt: This neoclassical limestone memorial with an observation deck houses a Civil War museum & gift shop.

It stands at almost 285 feet tall and features statues representing different military branches. Visitors can explore the Civil War museum at its base and ascend to an observation deck for stunning panoramic views of the city skyline.

excerpt: Massive food hall operating since 1866, with various vendors, a farmers market & a craft beer bar.

Additionally, guided tours of the Romanesque catacombs beneath Whistler Plaza are available for an extra fee.

Guests can savor dry-aged steaks while being surrounded by photo-lined hallways honoring notable visitors.

As you explore this National Historic Landmark through guided tours, you'll gain insight into life over a century ago while admiring the beautifully restored interiors and charming Victorian decor.

excerpt: This 1,700-acre park offers activities such as cross-country skiing, fishing & hiking.

The park offers a range of activities including cross-country skiing, fishing, hiking, and mountain biking. address: 6000 N Post Rd, Indianapolis, IN 46216, USA

Designed by renowned German landscape architect George Kessler in 1916, the conservatory boasts an elegant art-deco style with expansive glass panels and houses an array of plant species including ferns, bananas, palms, orchids, coffee, and vanilla.

excerpt: Strolling, paddleboating & kayaking along a canal where paths & bridges are decorated with artwork.

name: Indianapolis Canal Walk
address: Canal Walk, Indianapolis, IN 46202, USA

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Indianapolis, Lockerbie Square Historic District stands as the city's oldest preserved residential neighborhood, a testament to its rich history. Established in the mid-19th century and originally known as Germantown due to an influx of German settlers, this charming area is named after Jannett Smith Lockerbie McOuat and her father George Murray Lockerbie.

detail_description: The Indiana State Capitol, located in downtown Indianapolis, is a significant and iconic building that represents the state's rich history. Built in 1888 by architect Edwin May, it showcases a captivating mix of Renaissance Revival and Classical architectural styles. Serving as the home of the Indiana General Assembly, the Office of the Governor of Indiana, and the Supreme Court of Indiana, this historical site stands as a reminder of Indiana's vibrant past.

excerpt: Broad Ripple has a free-spirited vibe, with laid-back cafes, global eateries, lively brewpubs and happening clubs. The society offers insights into Indianapolis' humble beginnings and its evolution over the years, with collections covering social services, politics, women in Indiana, and the Civil War.
